- `start()`: add kit scanning (`g.kits()`) and `plugin:initialized` subscription
- `start()`: add permission dependency-scoping validation with `console.warn` + drop
- `weave()`: role lookup must check kit-contributed registry in addition to guild config
- Apparatus declaration: add `consumes: ['roles']`

Current `RoleDefinition` (lines 78–86):
```typescript
export interface RoleDefinition {
  permissions: string[];
  strict?: boolean;
}
```

Current `LoomConfig` (lines 89–92):
```typescript
export interface LoomConfig {
  roles?: Record<string, RoleDefinition>;
}
```

Current `start()` (lines 173–219): reads `config = g.guildConfig().loom ?? {}`, reads `charterContent`, reads `roleInstructions` Map. Does NOT call `g.kits()`, does NOT subscribe to `plugin:initialized`.

Current `weave()` (lines 109–165): looks up `config.roles[request.role]` — a plain key lookup against the guild config `LoomConfig.roles`. No kit-contributed registry.

**`packages/plugins/loom/src/index.ts`**
Needs to export any new types (e.g. `KitRoleDefinition`, `LoomKit`) via named exports. May also need to add a `consumes: ['roles']` to the default-exported apparatus if factored out there (currently the apparatus is created by `createLoom()` called inline).

**`packages/plugins/loom/src/loom.test.ts`**
New test cases required for:
- Kit-contributed role registration and weave() resolution
- Namespacing (`{pluginId}.{roleName}`)
- Guild override wins over kit role
- Permission dependency-scoping validation (valid/invalid permissions)
- `instructionsFile` loading from node_modules
- Inline `instructions` field
- `plugin:initialized` event handling for apparatus supportKits

---

### Types & Signatures

**`RoleDefinition`** (current, `loom.ts` line 78)
```typescript
export interface RoleDefinition {
  permissions: string[];
  strict?: boolean;
}
```
Used for guild-configured roles (in `LoomConfig.roles`). No `instructions` fields — instructions for guild roles come from `{home}/roles/{roleName}.md`.

**`LoomConfig`** (current, `loom.ts` line 89)
```typescript
export interface LoomConfig {
  roles?: Record<string, RoleDefinition>;
}
```
Config section in `guild.json` under the `loom` plugin id. Accessed via `g.guildConfig().loom`.

**`WeaveRequest`** (current, `loom.ts` line 26)
```typescript
export interface WeaveRequest {
  role?: string;
}
```
`role` is currently a bare name (e.g. `'artificer'`). With kit-contributed roles, it may also accept a qualified name (`'git.artificer'`) depending on the resolution strategy chosen.

**`AnimaWeave`** (current, `loom.ts` line 46)
```typescript
export interface AnimaWeave {
  systemPrompt?: string;
  tools?: ResolvedTool[];
  environment?: Record<string, string>;
}
```
No changes required.

**`LoomApi`** (current, `loom.ts` line 60)
```typescript
export interface LoomApi {
  weave(request: WeaveRequest): Promise<AnimaWeave>;
}
```
No changes required — the API shape remains stable.

---

### New Types Needed

**`KitRoleDefinition`** (new)
```typescript
export interface KitRoleDefinition {
  permissions: string[];
  strict?: boolean;
  instructions?: string;         // inline instructions text
  instructionsFile?: string;     // path relative to kit's npm package root
}
```

**`LoomKit`** (new — kit interface for type-safety, similar to SpiderKit, ClockworksKit)
```typescript
export interface LoomKit {
  roles?: Record<string, KitRoleDefinition>;
}
```
Published so kit authors can `satisfies LoomKit` for type safety.

---

### Adjacent: Read-Only Reference

**`packages/framework/core/src/plugin.ts`** — `Kit`, `Apparatus`, `LoadedKit`, `LoadedApparatus`, `LoadedPlugin`, `isLoadedKit`, `isLoadedApparatus`
```typescript
export type Kit = {
  requires?:   string[]
  recommends?: string[]
  [key: string]: unknown
}

export interface LoadedKit {
  readonly packageName: string
  readonly id:          string
  readonly version:     string
  readonly kit:         Kit
}

export interface LoadedApparatus {
  readonly packageName: string
  readonly id:          string
  readonly version:     string
  readonly apparatus:   Apparatus
}
```

The `Apparatus.consumes?: string[]` field is what the Loom will use for `consumes: ['roles']`. Currently the Loom apparatus has `requires: ['tools']` and no `consumes`.

**`packages/framework/core/src/guild.ts`** — `Guild.kits()` returns `LoadedKit[]`; `Guild.home` provides guild root.

**`packages/plugins/tools/src/instrumentarium.ts`** — The canonical consumer pattern:
- In `start()`: calls `g.kits()` to scan already-loaded kits (line 345), then subscribes `ctx.on('plugin:initialized', ...)` (line 351) for apparatus supportKits
- The `plugin:initialized` handler skips kits (`if (isLoadedApparatus(loaded))`) — kits are all loaded before apparatus start, so they're covered by the initial `g.kits()` scan
- `preloadInstructions()` (line 196): resolves `instructionsFile` via `path.join(guildHome, 'node_modules', packageName, tool.instructionsFile)` — the same pattern the Loom will need for kit role instructionsFiles

**`packages/plugins/spider/src/spider.ts`** — Same pattern: `g.kits()` then `ctx.on('plugin:initialized', ...)` for engines/block-types.

---

## Full Loom `start()` — Current Implementation

```typescript
start(_ctx: StartupContext): void {
  const g = guild();
  config = g.guildConfig().loom ?? {};
  const home = g.home;

  // Read charter content at startup and cache it.
  charterContent = undefined;
  const charterFilePath = path.join(home, 'charter.md');
  try {
    charterContent = fs.readFileSync(charterFilePath, 'utf-8');
  } catch (err: unknown) {
    if ((err as NodeJS.ErrnoException).code !== 'ENOENT') throw err;
    // No charter.md — check for charter/ directory.
    // ... reads charter/ dir files alphabetically
  }

  // Read role instruction files at startup for all configured roles.
  roleInstructions = new Map();
  if (config.roles) {
    for (const roleName of Object.keys(config.roles)) {
      const rolePath = path.join(home, 'roles', `${roleName}.md`);
      try {
        const content = fs.readFileSync(rolePath, 'utf-8');
        if (content) {
          roleInstructions.set(roleName, content);
        }
      } catch {
        // File doesn't exist — silently omit.
      }
    }
  }
},
```

No kit scanning, no event subscription.

---

## Full Loom `weave()` — Role Resolution (Current)

```typescript
// Resolve tools if a role is provided and has a definition.
if (request.role && config.roles) {
  const roleDef = config.roles[request.role];
  if (roleDef) {
    // ... call instrumentarium.resolve()
  }
}

// ...

// System prompt: role instructions layer
if (request.role && roleInstructions.has(request.role)) {
  layers.push(roleInstructions.get(request.role)!);
}
```

Role lookup is a plain `config.roles[request.role]` — no fallback, no qualified name lookup.

---

## Comparable Kit Consumer Patterns

### Instrumentarium (`packages/plugins/tools/src/instrumentarium.ts`)

```typescript
// In start():
registry.setHome(g.home);

// Register own supportKit tools first
for (const t of [toolsList, toolsShow]) {
  registry.registerTool(t, 'tools');
}

// Scan all already-loaded kits
for (const kit of g.kits()) {
  registry.register(kit);
}

// Subscribe for apparatus supportKits
ctx.on('plugin:initialized', (plugin: unknown) => {
  const loaded = plugin as LoadedPlugin;
  if (isLoadedApparatus(loaded)) {    // skip kits — already scanned
    registry.register(loaded);
  }
});
```

The `register(plugin)` method:
```typescript
register(plugin: LoadedPlugin): void {
  const pluginId = plugin.id;
  const packageName = plugin.packageName;

  if (isLoadedKit(plugin)) {
    this.registerToolsFromKit(pluginId, packageName, plugin.kit);
  } else if (isLoadedApparatus(plugin)) {
    if (plugin.apparatus.supportKit) {
      this.registerToolsFromKit(pluginId, packageName, plugin.apparatus.supportKit);
    }
  }
}
```

Key observation: both kits and apparatus supportKits are processed the same way in `register()`. The only difference in the startup flow is that kits are already loaded before start() runs (so scanned via `g.kits()`), while apparatus supportKits fire via `plugin:initialized` after their apparatus starts.

**The `plugin:initialized` handler only processes `isLoadedApparatus` — not kits — because kits are ALL loaded before any apparatus starts.**

### Spider (`packages/plugins/spider/src/spider.ts`)

Same exact pattern for block types and engines:
```typescript
for (const kit of g.kits()) {
  blockTypeRegistry.register(kit);
}
ctx.on('plugin:initialized', (plugin: unknown) => {
  const loaded = plugin as LoadedPlugin;
  if (isLoadedApparatus(loaded)) {
    blockTypeRegistry.register(loaded);
  }
});
```

---

## Permission Format & Dependency Scoping

Current permission format: `{plugin}:{level}` strings.
- `stacks:read`, `stacks:write`, `*:*`, `stacks:*`
- Used in `InstrumentariumApi.resolve({ permissions: [...] })`
- Parse logic in `instrumentarium.ts`: `parseGrant()` splits on first `:`

For dependency-scoping (requirement 4):
- A kit with `id: 'acme/myplugin'` and `requires: ['stacks']` and `recommends: ['animator']`
- Valid permissions: `acme/myplugin:read`, `stacks:write`, `animator:*`
- Invalid permissions: `clerk:read` (clerk not declared in requires/recommends)
- Wildcard ambiguity: `*:*` — does this reference "undeclared plugins"? Not explicit in brief.

The validation needs access to: `kit.id`, `kit.kit.requires ?? []`, `kit.kit.recommends ?? []`.

---

## `instructionsFile` Resolution Pattern

From Instrumentarium `preloadInstructions()`:
```typescript
const packageDir = path.join(this.guildHome, 'node_modules', packageName);
const filePath = path.join(packageDir, tool.instructionsFile);
const content = fs.readFileSync(filePath, 'utf-8');
```

For kit-contributed role `instructionsFile`, the same pattern applies. The Loom has `g.home` (= `guildHome`), and `LoadedKit.packageName` (= npm package name). So the path is:
```
{home}/node_modules/{packageName}/{instructionsFile}
```

On failure: warn and proceed (same as Instrumentarium: `console.warn(...)` + return tool without instructions).

---

## Namespacing & `weave()` Resolution

### Current behavior
`weave({ role: 'artificer' })` → `config.roles['artificer']` — direct key lookup.

### New requirement
Kit-contributed roles are stored under `{pluginId}.{roleName}` (qualified name). Two lookup paths exist for `weave()`:
1. Guild config: checked first, keyed by whatever name the guild operator used (could be bare `artificer` or qualified `git.artificer`)
2. Kit-contributed registry: keyed by qualified name `git.artificer`

**Ambiguity in the brief:**
> "Plugin others only specify the roleName, and the loom applies the plugin namespace automatically."

This statement is ambiguous:
- **Interpretation A**: Callers of `weave()` pass bare names only (e.g. `'artificer'`). The Loom searches both guild roles and kit roles. For kit roles, it tries `{anyPluginId}.{roleName}` for each loaded kit.
- **Interpretation B**: The Loom accepts both bare and qualified names. Bare names resolve to guild-configured roles. Qualified names resolve to kit-contributed roles. The phrase means "when writing kit code (standing orders, etc.), authors use bare names."
- **Interpretation C**: The phrase is only relevant to standing-order config — operators configure standing orders with bare role names, and the Loom namespace-resolves them. The `weave()` call always uses the final resolved name.

If A: need to handle the case where multiple kits contribute a role with the same bare name — which one wins? (Priority/ordering question.)
If B: existing callers (Animator calling `loom.weave({ role: 'artificer' })`) continue to work against guild roles unchanged.

This is a **key decision point** that must be flagged.

---

## Guild Override Semantics (Requirement 5)

"A guild-defined role in `loom.roles` with the same qualified name fully overrides the kit-contributed role — no merging."

This means: if a kit contributes `git.artificer`, and the guild config has `loom.roles['git.artificer']`, the guild definition wins. The kit's permissions, strict, and instructions are completely ignored.

The check is against the **qualified name** — a guild role named `artificer` does NOT override a kit role named `git.artificer`.

Implementation: when building the role registry, insert kit-contributed roles first, then overlay with guild-configured roles (for any matching qualified names).

---

## Loom Apparatus Declaration (Current)

```typescript
return {
  apparatus: {
    requires: ['tools'],
    provides: api,
    start(_ctx: StartupContext): void { ... },
  },
};
```

New: add `consumes: ['roles']` so Arbor can warn when a kit contributes `roles` but no apparatus consumes them.

---

## Doc/Code Discrepancies

1. **loom.test.ts line 67**: the mock `guildConfig()` returns `loom: opts.loomConfig` — but it also sets `workshops: {}` and `roles: {}` at the top level of GuildConfig, which are not defined in the current `GuildConfig` interface in `guild-config.ts`. These appear to be stale legacy fields from an older version of the config model. The tests compile because of TypeScript's `as never` cast. This is a test artifact, not a real discrepancy.

2. **docs/architecture/apparatus/loom.md** says "Role Ownership and Permission Grants" as a future section. The doc correctly describes the current `guild.json` `loom.roles` format. There is no mention of kit-contributed roles in the docs yet.

3. **docs/architecture/kit-components.md** describes the role-gating model using a different schema (e.g. `roles.steward.tools`, `baseTools`, `roles.artificer.seats`) that does not match the actual `guild.json` structure the code uses (which has `loom.roles.{name}.permissions`). This doc appears to be from a pre-refactor design. The code is the ground truth.

4. **docs/reference/schema.md** references `roster` and `anima_compositions` tables, `commissions`, `commission_assignments` — a legacy data model. These are not present in the current codebase packages.

---

## Existing Test Coverage (Tests that will need updating/extending)

**`packages/plugins/loom/src/loom.test.ts`** — Full test suite for the Loom.
- Uses a `setupGuild()` helper that sets `loom: opts.loomConfig` in a fake guildConfig
- Uses `mockInstrumentarium()` for tool resolution tests
- Tests cover: tool resolution, strict mode, git identity, charter composition (file, directory), role instructions composition (file-based), composition order, startup caching, backward compatibility
- **Missing tests for**: kit-contributed roles, qualified name resolution, permission dependency-scoping, instructionsFile loading from node_modules, guild override semantics

**`packages/plugins/tools/src/instrumentarium.test.ts`** — Reference for how Instrumentarium tests handle kit scanning and `plugin:initialized`. Uses `wireGuild()` + `startInstrumentarium()` helper pattern with `LoadedKit[]` and `LoadedApparatus[]`.

---

## Scratch Notes / TODOs

- **No prior commissions** touching kit-contributed roles found in the codebase.
- **No scratch notes or TODOs** in the loom code referencing kit contributions.
- The `docs/architecture/apparatus/loom.md` future section on role ownership notes that "Role configuration lives in guild.json under the Loom's plugin id" — the current implementation matches this. Kit-contributed roles are a new addition not yet anticipated in the docs.

---

## Files NOT Affected

- `packages/framework/arbor/src/arbor.ts` — Arbor's `collectStartupWarnings` already handles kits contributing types with no consumer via `consumes` cross-reference. Adding `consumes: ['roles']` to the Loom apparatus will just make warnings work for the `roles` key. No Arbor changes needed.
- `packages/framework/arbor/src/guild-lifecycle.ts` — No changes needed.
- `packages/framework/core/src/plugin.ts` — No changes needed. `Kit` is already an open record with `[key: string]: unknown`.
- `packages/framework/core/src/guild-config.ts` — No changes needed. The `GuildConfig` interface stays as-is; the Loom augments it via `declare module` in `index.ts`.
- `packages/plugins/tools/src/instrumentarium.ts` — Not affected.
- `packages/plugins/animator/src/animator.ts` — Not affected; calls `loom.weave({ role })` with a string.
- All other plugin packages — Not affected.

---

## Summary of Net Changes

| File | Change |
|------|--------|
| `packages/plugins/loom/src/loom.ts` | New types (`KitRoleDefinition`, `LoomKit`); modify `start()` to scan kits + subscribe to events; add permission scoping validation; modify `weave()` for kit role lookup; add `consumes: ['roles']` |
| `packages/plugins/loom/src/index.ts` | Export new types |
| `packages/plugins/loom/src/loom.test.ts` | New test cases for kit-contributed roles |

